Creating a simple Python lexer in Rust involves using Rust's pattern matching and string manipulation features to recognize different elements of the Python language, such as comments, keywords, identifiers, and literals. Below is an example of a very basic Rust implementation of such a lexer that can handle a limited subset of Python syntax, such as identifiers, def keyword, numbers, parentheses, colons, newlines, and the return keyword.

```rust
use std::str::Chars;
use std::iter::Peekable;

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]
enum Token {
    Identifier(String),
    Def,
    Return,
    Number(String),
    OpenParenthesis,
    CloseParenthesis,
    Colon,
    Newline,
    Indent,
    Dedent,
    EndOfFile,
}

struct Lexer<'a> {
    chars: Peekable<Chars<'a>>,
    current_indent: usize,
    indent_stack: Vec<usize>,
}

impl<'a> Lexer<'a> {
    fn new(input: &'a str) -> Self {
        Self {
            chars: input.chars().peekable(),
            current_indent: 0,
            indent_stack: vec![0],
        }
    }

    fn next_token(&mut self) -> Option<Token> {
        while let Some(&ch) = self.chars.peek() {
            return match ch {
                '#' => {
                    // Skip comments by consuming characters until a newline is reached.
                    while let Some(ch) = self.chars.next() {
                        if ch == '\n' {
                            break;
                        }
                    }
                    continue;
                }
                ch if ch.is_alphabetic() || ch == '_' => {
                    // Parse an identifier or keyword.
                    let mut identifier = String::new();
                    while let Some(&ch) = self.chars.peek() {
                        if ch.is_alphanumeric() || ch == '_' {
                            identifier.push(self.chars.next().unwrap());
                        } else {
                            break;
                        }
                    }
                    match identifier.as_str() {
                        "def" => Some(Token::Def),
                        "return" => Some(Token::Return),
                        _ => Some(Token::Identifier(identifier)),
                    }
                }
                '(' => {
                    self.chars.next();
                    Some(Token::OpenParenthesis)
                }
                ')' => {
                    self.chars.next();
                    Some(Token::CloseParenthesis)
                }
                ':' => {
                    self.chars.next();
                    Some(Token::Colon)
                }
                ch if ch.is_digit(10) => {
                    // Parse a number.
                    let mut number = String::new();
                    while let Some(&ch) = self.chars.peek() {
                        if ch.is_digit(10) {
                            number.push(self.chars.next().unwrap());
                        } else {
                            break;
                        }
                    }
                    Some(Token::Number(number))
                }
                '\n' => {
                    self.chars.next();
                    Some(Token::Newline)
                }
                ch if ch.is_whitespace() => {
                    // Skip whitespace outside of indentation context.
                    self.chars.next();
                    continue;
                }
                _ => {
                    // Could add more token cases here.
                    None
                }
            };
        }
        // No more characters left to tokenize.
        None
    }
}

fn main() {
    let input = "#hihi\ndef sum(a, b):\n    if a<b:\n        return a\n\ndef min():\n    return 2";
    let mut lexer = Lexer::new(input);

    while let Some(token) = lexer.next_token() {
        println!("{:?}", token);
    }
}
```

This code defines a lexer with the `Lexer` struct, which keeps track of the characters to be lexed and the current indentation level. The `next_token` method returns the next available token or `None` if there are no more tokens to process.

Please note: this lexer doesn't cover all Python syntax, and the output for a full Python lexer would be a lot more complex because the Python syntax has many more elements that need to be taken into account, such as different types of operators, strings with various quoting styles, different number formats, and comprehensive whitespace and indentation handling. Additionally, a lexer typically does not execute the source code; instead, that's the task of an interpreter or compiler, which come after the lexing stage.

To properly handle indentation and dedentation, a Python lexer needs to track changes in indentation level. In Python, blocks of code are determined by their indentation levels, so we need to produce `Indent` and `Dedent` tokens when the indentation level changes.

Below is the updated Rust code that includes handling for indentation and dedentation:

```rust
use std::str::Chars;
use std::iter::Peekable;

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]
enum Token {
    Identifier(String),
    Def,
    Return,
    Number(String),
    OpenParenthesis,
    CloseParenthesis,
    Colon,
    Newline,
    Indent,
    Dedent,
    EndOfFile,
}

struct Lexer<'a> {
    chars: Peekable<Chars<'a>>,
    current_indent: usize,
    indent_levels: Vec<usize>,
    at_bol: bool, // At Beginning of Line
}

impl<'a> Lexer<'a> {
    fn new(input: &'a str) -> Self {
        Self {
            chars: input.chars().peekable(),
            current_indent: 0,
            indent_levels: Vec::new(),
            at_bol: true, // start at the beginning of the line
        }
    }

    fn next_token(&mut self) -> Option<Token> {
        while let Some(&ch) = self.chars.peek() {
            if self.at_bol {
                self.at_bol = false;
                let mut indent = 0;
                while let Some(&' ') = self.chars.peek() {
                    self.chars.next();
                    indent += 1;
                }
                if indent > self.current_indent {
                    self.indent_levels.push(self.current_indent);
                    self.current_indent = indent;
                    return Some(Token::Indent);
                } else if indent < self.current_indent {
                    while let Some(last_indent) = self.indent_levels.pop() {
                        self.current_indent = last_indent;
                        if indent == self.current_indent {
                            return Some(Token::Dedent);
                        }
                        if indent > self.current_indent {
                            // This is an error in a real Python lexer; we should report mismatched indentation
                            panic!("Mismatched indentation");
                        }
                    }
                }
            }

            return match ch {
                '#' => {
                    // Skip comments
                    while let Some(ch) = self.chars.next() {
                        if ch == '\n' {
                            self.at_bol = true;
                            break;
                        }
                    }
                    continue;
                }
                '\n' => {
                    self.chars.next();
                    self.at_bol = true;
                    return Some(Token::Newline);
                }
                '(' => {
                    self.chars.next();
                    Some(Token::OpenParenthesis)
                }
                ')' => {
                    self.chars.next();
                    Some(Token::CloseParenthesis)
                }
                ':' => {
                    self.chars.next();
                    Some(Token::Colon)
                }
                ch if ch.is_alphabetic() || ch == '_' => {
                    let mut identifier = String::new();
                    while let Some(&ch) = self.chars.peek() {
                        if ch.is_alphanumeric() || ch == '_' {
                            identifier.push(self.chars.next().unwrap());
                        } else {
                            break;
                        }
                    }
                    Some(match identifier.as_str() {
                        "def" => Token::Def,
                        "return" => Token::Return,
                        _ => Token::Identifier(identifier),
                    })
                }
                ch if ch.is_digit(10) => {
                    let mut number = String::new();
                    while let Some(&ch) = self.chars.peek() {
                        if ch.is_digit(10) {
                            number.push(self.chars.next().unwrap());
                        } else {
                            break;
                        }
                    }
                    Some(Token::Number(number))
                }
                ch if ch.is_whitespace() => {
                    // Skip whitespace
                    self.chars.next();
                    continue;
                }
                _ => {
                    // Other single characters
                    None
                }
            };
        }

        if !self.indent_levels.is_empty() {
            // Emit remaining Dedent tokens at the end of the file
            self.indent_levels.pop();
            Some(Token::Dedent)
        } else {
            None // End of the file
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let input = "#hihi\ndef sum(a, b):\n    if a<b:\n        return a\n\ndef min():\n    return 2";
    let mut lexer = Lexer::new(input);

    while let Some(token) = lexer.next_token() {
        println!("{:?}", token);
    }
}
```

This lexer will now emit `Indent` and `Dedent` tokens when the level of indentation increases or decreases. The lexer checks the indentation level at the beginning of each line. If the indentation level increased, it pushes onto the `indent_levels` stack and emits an `Indent` token. If the indentation level is less than the current indentation level, it pops from the `indent_levels` stack and emits a `Dedent` token until the stack reflects the current indentation level.

Please note again that this is a simplified lexer. A production-ready lexer for Python would need to handle tabs intelligently (as the Python interpreter does), account for empty lines and comments when determining indentation changes, and incorporate error handling for mismatched or inconsistent indentation.

